summary: “Just man up”- does identifying as a sexual abuse victim remove one’s masculinity?
title: “Just man up”- does identifying as a sexual abuse victim remove one’s masculinity?
body:
“I was always under threat, if I was not playing well, he would threaten me with violence as well as sexual abuse. He was a monster”. These words come from Paul Stewart, English former professional footballer. In his interview to the BBC, it is clear to observe the difficulty in his face, and the pain in his eyes when speaking about his past experience of suffering from sexual abuse, over a long period of time. Unfortunately, Paul Stewart is not the only victim within sport to open up about past sexual abuse (especially in football), which questions why male sexual abuse is still a taboo subject within the sporting society. 

Having an unwanted sexual experience can make any individual feel vulnerable, overwhelmed, and flooded by intense emotions. However, for males many feel this experience can compromise their masculinity, and consequently their whole identity. Hence, Gill and Tutty in 1998  found men “experience an overwhelming sense of failing to meet perceived social requirements of masculinity”. Therefore, does the blame sit within society for obeying to gender norms, separating society into two splits of male and female, and reinforcing to males at a young age they must be dominating, and fearless?

According to the work of Hunter, ‘sexual abuse of boys is not much studied because of the discomfort in society about it, the traditional roles that are shaken by the victimisation of men, and also because of homophobia’. Moreover, this may explain the conflict of power between coaches and young male players. Surely, if the abusing coach is aware of the personal conflicts the victim may experience; the culture of silence regarding male victims in sport; and the perceived risks of damaging a player’s reputation, this creates a devastating opportunity for the abuser to manipulate the coach-player relationship.

The intense pressure for males to appear masculine, and to not show any emotional weakness, can continue to occur after the sexual abuse has taken place. Parent and Bannon suggest, “in reaction to social pressure, and the social imperatives of masculinity, boys who are sexually abused sometimes also adopt sexist and hyper-masculine behaviours”. The concept of sport itself for many boys is a masculinity symbol; whereby the media may reinforce ideals of how they should behave as an athlete. Moreover, if the victim fears their masculine, heterosexual identity is at risk due to previous abuse, they may display higher levels of masculinity in their behaviours than usual.

I believe it is important we re-define ‘hegemonic masculinity’, a gender order theory from the early 1980’s which was to reinforce males’ power in Western society, and their dominant position in a social hierarchy. In regards to male sexual abuse victims; and male’s mental health in general, men continue to feel ashamed to speak about their experiences’ and emotions’. As this conflicts the stereotypes which were reinforced to them from such a young age. Does this suggest an urgency to destroy, and re-define what it means to be ‘male’ within our society? 

Overcoming such a traumatic experience can be daunting for any individual. Many may need time to come to the realisation on what has happened to them, and to overcome denial. In recent times, there has been a movement for male sexual abuse victims to break the silence, and share their experiences’ with others. One man on the BBC shares his story of overcoming sexual abuse, and the coping methods he used. Many may suggest men sharing their experiences, and breaking the silence is key to helping other victims in recovering from sexual abuse, as well as creating a more inclusive society.

N0670147

References:

Armstrong, J. (2016). Paul Stewart: I was sexually abused by coach who threatened to kill my family if I told anyone. Mirror. [online] Available at: https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/paul-stewart-sexually-abused-coach-9313094 [Accessed 6 Nov. 2018].

Gill, M. and Tutty, L. (1998). Sexual Identity Issues for Male Survivors of Childhood Sexual Abuse: A Qualitative Study. Journal of Child Sexual Abuse, 6(3), pp.31-47.

M. Hunter (Ed.) (1990), The sexually abused male: Prevalence, impact and treatment, Vol. 1, Lexington Books, Lexington, MA.

Parent, S. and Bannon, J. (2012). Sexual abuse in sport: What about boys?. Children and Youth Services Review, 34(2), pp.354-359.

Many may suggest men sharing their experiences, and breaking the silence is key to helping other victims in recovering from sexual abuse, as well as creating a more inclusive society.
